1171@dataclasses.dataclass
1172class AntsRegistrationStage:
1173    """
1174    Stage of the registration process.
1175    """
1176    transform: typing.Union[AntsRegistrationTransformRigid, AntsRegistrationTransformAffine, AntsRegistrationTransformCompositeAffine, AntsRegistrationTransformSimilarity, AntsRegistrationTransformTranslation, AntsRegistrationTransformBspline, AntsRegistrationTransformGaussianDisplacementField, AntsRegistrationTransformBsplineDisplacementField, AntsRegistrationTransformTimeVaryingVelocityField, AntsRegistrationTransformTimeVaryingBsplineVelocityField, AntsRegistrationTransformSyn, AntsRegistrationTransformBsplineSyn, AntsRegistrationTransformExponential, AntsRegistrationTransformBsplineExponential]
1177    """Several transform options are available. The gradientStep or learningRate
1178    characterizes the gradient descent optimization and is scaled appropriately
1179    for each transform using the shift scales estimator. Subsequent parameters
1180    are transform-specific and can be determined from the usage. For the
1181    B-spline transforms one can also specify the smoothing in terms of spline
1182    distance (i.e. knot spacing)."""
1183    metric: typing.Union[AntsRegistrationMetricAntsNeighbourhoodCrossCorrelation, AntsRegistrationMetricMutualInformation, AntsRegistrationMetricMattes, AntsRegistrationMetricMeanSquares, AntsRegistrationMetricDemons, AntsRegistrationMetricGlobalCorrelation, AntsRegistrationMetricEuclideanIcp, AntsRegistrationMetricPointSetExpectation, AntsRegistrationMetricJensenHavrdaCharvetTsallis, AntsRegistrationMetricIgdm]
1184    """These image metrics are available--- CC: ANTS neighborhood cross
1185    correlation, MI: Mutual information, Demons: (Thirion), MeanSquares, and GC:
1186    Global Correlation. The "metricWeight" variable is used to modulate the per
1187    stage weighting of the metrics. The metrics can also employ a sampling
1188    strategy defined by a sampling percentage. The sampling strategy defaults to
1189    'None' (aka a dense sampling of one sample per voxel), otherwise it defines
1190    a point set over which to optimize the metric. The point set can be on a
1191    regular lattice or a random lattice of points slightly perturbed to minimize
1192    aliasing artifacts. samplingPercentage defines the fraction of points to
1193    select from the domain. useGradientFilter specifies whether a
1194    smoothingfilter is applied when estimating the metric gradient.In addition,
1195    three point set metrics are available: Euclidean (ICP), Point-set
1196    expectation (PSE), and Jensen-Havrda-Charvet-Tsallis (JHCT)."""
1197    convergence: AntsRegistrationConvergence
1198    """Convergence is determined from the number of iterations per level and is
1199    determined by fitting a line to the normalized energy profile of the last N
1200    iterations (where N is specified by the window size) and determining the
1201    slope which is then compared with the convergence threshold. """
1202    smoothing_sigmas: str
1203    """Specify the sigma of gaussian smoothing at each level. Units are given in
1204    terms of voxels ('vox') or physical spacing ('mm'). Example usage is
1205    '4x2x1mm' and '4x2x1vox' where no units implies voxel spacing."""
1206    shrink_factors: str
1207    """Specify the shrink factor for the virtual domain (typically the fixed
1208    image) at each level."""
1209    use_histogram_matching: typing.Literal[0, 1] | None = None
1210    """Use histogram matching."""
1211    
1212    def run(
1213        self,
1214        execution: Execution,
1215    ) -> list[str]:
1216        """
1217        Build command line arguments. This method is called by the main command.
1218        
1219        Args:
1220            self: The sub-command object.
1221            execution: The execution object.
1222        Returns:
1223            
1224        """
1225        cargs = []
1226        cargs.extend(["--transform", *self.transform.run(execution)])
1227        cargs.extend(["--metric", *self.metric.run(execution)])
1228        cargs.extend(["--convergence", *self.convergence.run(execution)])
1229        cargs.extend(["--smoothing-sigmas", self.smoothing_sigmas])
1230        cargs.extend(["--shrink-factors", self.shrink_factors])
1231        if self.use_histogram_matching is not None:
1232            cargs.extend(["--use-histogram-matching", str(self.use_histogram_matching)])
1233        return cargs

1316    """The output is the warped moving image."""
1317    warp: OutputPathType | None
1318    """The output is the warp field."""

1321def ants_registration(
1322    stages: list[AntsRegistrationStage],
1323    dimensionality: typing.Literal[2, 3, 4] | None = None,
1324    output: str | None = None,
1325    save_state: str | None = None,
1326    restore_state: str | None = None,
1327    write_composite_transform: typing.Literal[0, 1] | None = None,
1328    print_similarity_measure_interval: int | None = None,
1329    write_interval_volumes: int | None = None,
1330    collapse_output_transforms: typing.Literal[1, 0] | None = None,
1331    initialize_transforms_per_stage: typing.Literal[1, 0] | None = None,
1332    interpolation: typing.Literal["Linear", "NearestNeighbor", "MultiLabel", "Gaussian", "BSpline", "CosineWindowedSinc", "WelchWindowedSinc", "HammingWindowedSinc", "LanczosWindowedSinc", "GenericLabel"] | None = None,
1333    restrict_deformation: list[typing.Literal[0, 1]] | None = None,
1334    initial_fixed_transform: str | None = None,
1335    initial_moving_transform: typing.Union[AntsRegistrationInitialMovingTransform, AntsRegistrationInitialMovingTransformUseInverse, AntsRegistrationInitialMovingTransformInitializationFeature] | None = None,
1336    winsorize_image_intensities: AntsRegistrationWinsorizeImageIntensities | None = None,
1337    masks: AntsRegistrationMasks | None = None,
1338    minc: typing.Literal[0, 1] | None = None,
1339    random_seed: int | None = None,
1340    verbose: typing.Literal[0, 1] | None = None,
1341    float_: typing.Literal[0, 1] | None = None,
1342    runner: Runner | None = None,
1343) -> AntsRegistrationOutputs:
1344    """
1345    antsRegistration by Advanced Normalization Tools (ANTs) Contributors.
1346    
1347    This program is a user-level registration application meant to utilize
1348    classes in ITK v4.0 and later. The user can specify any number of "stages"
1349    where a stage consists of a transform; an image metric; and iterations,
1350    shrink factors, and smoothing sigmas for each level. Note that explicitly
1351    setting the dimensionality, metric, transform, output, convergence,
1352    shrink-factors, and smoothing-sigmas parameters is mandatory.
1353    
1354    More information: https://github.com/ANTsX/ANTs
1355    
1356    Args:
1357        stages: Stages of the registration process.
1358        dimensionality: This option forces the image to be treated as a\
1359            specified-dimensional image. If not specified, we try to infer the\
1360            dimensionality from the input image.
1361        output: Specify the output transform prefix (output format is .nii.gz\
1362            ). Optionally, one can choose to warp the moving image to the fixed\
1363            space and, if the inverse transform exists, one can also output the\
1364            warped fixed image. Note that only the images specified in the first\
1365            metric call are warped. Use antsApplyTransforms to warp other images\
1366            using the resultant transform(s). When a composite transform is not\
1367            specified, linear transforms are specified with a '.mat' suffix and\
1368            displacement fields with a 'Warp.nii.gz' suffix (and\
1369            'InverseWarp.nii.gz', when applicable. In addition, for velocity-based\
1370            transforms, the full velocity field is written to file\
1371            ('VelocityField.nii.gz') as long as the collapse transforms flag is\
1372            turned off ('-z 0').
1373        save_state: Specify the output file for the current state of the\
1374            registration. The state file is written to an hdf5 composite file. It\
1375            is specially usefull if we want to save the current state of a SyN\
1376            registration to the disk, so we can load and restore that later to\
1377            continue the next registration process directly started from the last\
1378            saved state. The output file of this flag is the same as the\
1379            write-composite-transform, unless the last transform is a SyN\
1380            transform. In that case, the inverse displacement field of the SyN\
1381            transform is also added to the output composite transform. Again notice\
1382            that this file cannot be treated as a transform, and restore-state\
1383            option must be used to load the written file by this flag.
1384        restore_state: Specify the initial state of the registration which get\
1385            immediately used to directly initialize the registration process. The\
1386            flag is mutually exclusive with other intialization flags.If this flag\
1387            is used, none of the initial-moving-transform and\
1388            initial-fixed-transform cannot be used.
1389        write_composite_transform: Boolean specifying whether or not the\
1390            composite transform (and its inverse, if it exists) should be written\
1391            to an hdf5 composite file. This is false by default so that only the\
1392            transform for each stage is written to file.
1393        print_similarity_measure_interval: Prints out the CC similarity metric\
1394            measure between the full-size input fixed and the transformed moving\
1395            images at each iteration a value of 0 (the default) indicates that the\
1396            full scale computation should not take placeany value greater than 0\
1397            represents the interval of full scale metric computation.
1398        write_interval_volumes: Writes out the output volume at each iteration.\
1399            It helps to present the registration process as a short movie a value\
1400            of 0 (the default) indicates that this option should not take placeany\
1401            value greater than 0 represents the interval between the iterations\
1402            which outputs are written to the disk.
1403        collapse_output_transforms: Collapse output transforms. Specifically,\
1404            enabling this option combines all adjacent transforms where possible.\
1405            All adjacent linear transforms are written to disk in the form of an\
1406            itk affine transform (called xxxGenericAffine.mat).\
1407            Similarly, all adjacent displacement field transforms are combined\
1408            when written to disk (e.g. xxxWarp.nii.gz and xxxInverseWarp.nii.gz\
1409            (if available)). Also, an output composite transform including the\
1410            collapsed transforms is written to the disk (called\
1411            outputCollapsed(Inverse)Composite).
1412        initialize_transforms_per_stage: Initialize linear transforms from the\
1413            previous stage. By enabling this option, the current linear stage\
1414            transform is directly intialized from the previous stage's linear\
1415            transform; this allows multiple linear stages to be run where each\
1416            stage directly updates the estimated linear transform from the previous\
1417            stage. (e.g. Translation -> Rigid -> Affine).
1418        interpolation: Several interpolation options are available in ITK.\
1419            These have all been made available. Currently the interpolator choice\
1420            is only used to warp (and possibly inverse warp) the final output\
1421            image(s).
1422        restrict_deformation: This option allows the user to restrict the\
1423            optimization of the displacement field, translation, rigid or affine\
1424            transform on a per-component basis. For example, if one wants to limit\
1425            the deformation or rotation of 3-D volume to the first two dimensions,\
1426            this is possible by specifying a weight vector of '1x1x0' for a\
1427            deformation field or '1x1x0x1x1x0' for a rigid transformation.\
1428            Low-dimensional restriction only works if there are no preceding\
1429            transformations.All stages up to and including the desired stage must\
1430            have this option specified,even if they should not be restricted (in\
1431            which case specify 1x1x1...).
1432        initial_fixed_transform: Specify the initial fixed transform(s) which\
1433            get immediately incorporated into the composite transform. The order of\
1434            the transforms is stack-esque in that the last transform specified on\
1435            the command line is the first to be applied. In addition to\
1436            initialization with ITK transforms, the user can perform an initial\
1437            translation alignment by specifying the fixed and moving images and\
1438            selecting an initialization feature. These features include using the\
1439            geometric center of the images (=0), the image intensities (=1), or the\
1440            origin of the images (=2).
1441        initial_moving_transform: Specify the initial moving transform(s) which\
1442            get immediately incorporated into the composite transform. The order of\
1443            the transforms is stack-esque in that the last transform specified on\
1444            the command line is the first to be applied. In addition to\
1445            initialization with ITK transforms, the user can perform an initial\
1446            translation alignment by specifying the fixed and moving images and\
1447            selecting an initialization feature. These features include using the\
1448            geometric center of the images (=0), the image intensities (=1), or the\
1449            origin of the images (=2).
1450        winsorize_image_intensities: Winsorize data based on specified\
1451            quantiles.
1452        masks: Image masks to limit voxels considered by the metric. Two\
1453            options are allowed for mask specification: 1) Either the user\
1454            specifies a single mask to be used for all stages or 2) the user\
1455            specifies a mask for each stage. With the latter one can select to\
1456            which stages masks are applied by supplying valid file names. If the\
1457            file does not exist, a mask will not be used for that stage. Note that\
1458            we handle the fixed and moving masks separately to enforce this\
1459            constraint.
1460        minc: Use MINC file formats for transformations.
1461        random_seed: Random seed.
1462        verbose: Verbose output.
1463        float_: Use 'float' instead of 'double' for computations.
1464        runner: Command runner.
1465    Returns:
1466        NamedTuple of outputs (described in `AntsRegistrationOutputs`).
1467    """
1468    runner = runner or get_global_runner()
1469    if write_interval_volumes is not None and not (0 <= write_interval_volumes): 
1470        raise ValueError(f"'write_interval_volumes' must be greater than 0 <= x but was {write_interval_volumes}")
1471    if restrict_deformation is not None and not (3 <= len(restrict_deformation) <= 6): 
1472        raise ValueError(f"Length of 'restrict_deformation' must be between 3 and 6 but was {len(restrict_deformation)}")
1473    if random_seed is not None and not (1 <= random_seed): 
1474        raise ValueError(f"'random_seed' must be greater than 1 <= x but was {random_seed}")
1475    execution = runner.start_execution(ANTS_REGISTRATION_METADATA)
1476    cargs = []
1477    cargs.append("antsRegistration")
1478    if dimensionality is not None:
1479        cargs.extend(["--dimensionality", str(dimensionality)])
1480    if output is not None:
1481        cargs.extend(["-o", output])
1482    if save_state is not None:
1483        cargs.extend(["-j", save_state])
1484    if restore_state is not None:
1485        cargs.extend(["-k", restore_state])
1486    if write_composite_transform is not None:
1487        cargs.extend(["-a", str(write_composite_transform)])
1488    if print_similarity_measure_interval is not None:
1489        cargs.extend(["-p", str(print_similarity_measure_interval)])
1490    if write_interval_volumes is not None:
1491        cargs.extend(["--write-interval-volumes", str(write_interval_volumes)])
1492    if collapse_output_transforms is not None:
1493        cargs.extend(["--collapse-output-transforms", str(collapse_output_transforms)])
1494    if initialize_transforms_per_stage is not None:
1495        cargs.extend(["-i", str(initialize_transforms_per_stage)])
1496    if interpolation is not None:
1497        cargs.extend(["--interpolation", interpolation])
1498    if restrict_deformation is not None:
1499        cargs.extend(["-g", "x".join(map(str, restrict_deformation))])
1500    if initial_fixed_transform is not None:
1501        cargs.extend(["-q", initial_fixed_transform])
1502    if initial_moving_transform is not None:
1503        cargs.extend(["--initial-moving-transform", *initial_moving_transform.run(execution)])
1504    cargs.extend([a for c in [s.run(execution) for s in stages] for a in c])
1505    if winsorize_image_intensities is not None:
1506        cargs.extend(["--winsorize-image-intensities", *winsorize_image_intensities.run(execution)])
1507    if masks is not None:
1508        cargs.extend(["--masks", *masks.run(execution)])
1509    if minc is not None:
1510        cargs.extend(["--minc", str(minc)])
1511    if random_seed is not None:
1512        cargs.extend(["--random-seed", str(random_seed)])
1513    if verbose is not None:
1514        cargs.extend(["-v", str(verbose)])
1515    ret = AntsRegistrationOutputs(
1516        root=execution.output_file("."),
1517        generic_affine=execution.output_file(f"{output}0GenericAffine.mat") if output is not None else None,
1518        inverse_warped=execution.output_file(f"{output}InverseWarped.nii.gz") if output is not None else None,
1519        inverse_warp=execution.output_file(f"{output}1InverseWarp.nii.gz", optional=True) if output is not None else None,
1520        warped=execution.output_file(f"{output}Warped.nii.gz") if output is not None else None,
1521        warp=execution.output_file(f"{output}1Warp.nii.gz", optional=True) if output is not None else None,
1522    )
1523    execution.run(cargs)
1524    return ret

AntsRegistrationStage( transform: Union[AntsRegistrationTransformRigid, AntsRegistrationTransformAffine, AntsRegistrationTransformCompositeAffine, AntsRegistrationTransformSimilarity, AntsRegistrationTransformTranslation, AntsRegistrationTransformBspline, AntsRegistrationTransformGaussianDisplacementField, AntsRegistrationTransformBsplineDisplacementField, AntsRegistrationTransformTimeVaryingVelocityField, AntsRegistrationTransformTimeVaryingBsplineVelocityField, AntsRegistrationTransformSyn, AntsRegistrationTransformBsplineSyn, AntsRegistrationTransformExponential, AntsRegistrationTransformBsplineExponential], metric: Union[AntsRegistrationMetricAntsNeighbourhoodCrossCorrelation, AntsRegistrationMetricMutualInformation, AntsRegistrationMetricMattes, AntsRegistrationMetricMeanSquares, AntsRegistrationMetricDemons, AntsRegistrationMetricGlobalCorrelation, AntsRegistrationMetricEuclideanIcp, AntsRegistrationMetricPointSetExpectation, AntsRegistrationMetricJensenHavrdaCharvetTsallis, AntsRegistrationMetricIgdm], convergence: AntsRegistrationConvergence, smoothing_sigmas: str, shrink_factors: str, use_histogram_matching: Optional[Literal[0, 1]] = None)
transform: Union[AntsRegistrationTransformRigid, AntsRegistrationTransformAffine, AntsRegistrationTransformCompositeAffine, AntsRegistrationTransformSimilarity, AntsRegistrationTransformTranslation, AntsRegistrationTransformBspline, AntsRegistrationTransformGaussianDisplacementField, AntsRegistrationTransformBsplineDisplacementField, AntsRegistrationTransformTimeVaryingVelocityField, AntsRegistrationTransformTimeVaryingBsplineVelocityField, AntsRegistrationTransformSyn, AntsRegistrationTransformBsplineSyn, AntsRegistrationTransformExponential, AntsRegistrationTransformBsplineExponential]

Several transform options are available. The gradientStep or learningRate characterizes the gradient descent optimization and is scaled appropriately for each transform using the shift scales estimator. Subsequent parameters are transform-specific and can be determined from the usage. For the B-spline transforms one can also specify the smoothing in terms of spline distance (i.e. knot spacing).

metric: Union[AntsRegistrationMetricAntsNeighbourhoodCrossCorrelation, AntsRegistrationMetricMutualInformation, AntsRegistrationMetricMattes, AntsRegistrationMetricMeanSquares, AntsRegistrationMetricDemons, AntsRegistrationMetricGlobalCorrelation, AntsRegistrationMetricEuclideanIcp, AntsRegistrationMetricPointSetExpectation, AntsRegistrationMetricJensenHavrdaCharvetTsallis, AntsRegistrationMetricIgdm]

These image metrics are available--- CC: ANTS neighborhood cross correlation, MI: Mutual information, Demons: (Thirion), MeanSquares, and GC: Global Correlation. The "metricWeight" variable is used to modulate the per stage weighting of the metrics. The metrics can also employ a sampling strategy defined by a sampling percentage. The sampling strategy defaults to 'None' (aka a dense sampling of one sample per voxel), otherwise it defines a point set over which to optimize the metric. The point set can be on a regular lattice or a random lattice of points slightly perturbed to minimize aliasing artifacts. samplingPercentage defines the fraction of points to select from the domain. useGradientFilter specifies whether a smoothingfilter is applied when estimating the metric gradient.In addition, three point set metrics are available: Euclidean (ICP), Point-set expectation (PSE), and Jensen-Havrda-Charvet-Tsallis (JHCT).

convergence: AntsRegistrationConvergence

Convergence is determined from the number of iterations per level and is determined by fitting a line to the normalized energy profile of the last N iterations (where N is specified by the window size) and determining the slope which is then compared with the convergence threshold.

smoothing_sigmas: str

Specify the sigma of gaussian smoothing at each level. Units are given in terms of voxels ('vox') or physical spacing ('mm'). Example usage is '4x2x1mm' and '4x2x1vox' where no units implies voxel spacing.

shrink_factors: str

Specify the shrink factor for the virtual domain (typically the fixed image) at each level.

use_histogram_matching: Optional[Literal[0, 1]] = None

Use histogram matching.

antsRegistration by Advanced Normalization Tools (ANTs) Contributors.

This program is a user-level registration application meant to utilize classes in ITK v4.0 and later. The user can specify any number of "stages" where a stage consists of a transform; an image metric; and iterations, shrink factors, and smoothing sigmas for each level. Note that explicitly setting the dimensionality, metric, transform, output, convergence, shrink-factors, and smoothing-sigmas parameters is mandatory.

More information: https://github.com/ANTsX/ANTs

Arguments:
  • stages: Stages of the registration process.
  • dimensionality: This option forces the image to be treated as a specified-dimensional image. If not specified, we try to infer the dimensionality from the input image.
  • output: Specify the output transform prefix (output format is .nii.gz ). Optionally, one can choose to warp the moving image to the fixed space and, if the inverse transform exists, one can also output the warped fixed image. Note that only the images specified in the first metric call are warped. Use antsApplyTransforms to warp other images using the resultant transform(s). When a composite transform is not specified, linear transforms are specified with a '.mat' suffix and displacement fields with a 'Warp.nii.gz' suffix (and 'InverseWarp.nii.gz', when applicable. In addition, for velocity-based transforms, the full velocity field is written to file ('VelocityField.nii.gz') as long as the collapse transforms flag is turned off ('-z 0').
  • save_state: Specify the output file for the current state of the registration. The state file is written to an hdf5 composite file. It is specially usefull if we want to save the current state of a SyN registration to the disk, so we can load and restore that later to continue the next registration process directly started from the last saved state. The output file of this flag is the same as the write-composite-transform, unless the last transform is a SyN transform. In that case, the inverse displacement field of the SyN transform is also added to the output composite transform. Again notice that this file cannot be treated as a transform, and restore-state option must be used to load the written file by this flag.
  • restore_state: Specify the initial state of the registration which get immediately used to directly initialize the registration process. The flag is mutually exclusive with other intialization flags.If this flag is used, none of the initial-moving-transform and initial-fixed-transform cannot be used.
  • write_composite_transform: Boolean specifying whether or not the composite transform (and its inverse, if it exists) should be written to an hdf5 composite file. This is false by default so that only the transform for each stage is written to file.
  • print_similarity_measure_interval: Prints out the CC similarity metric measure between the full-size input fixed and the transformed moving images at each iteration a value of 0 (the default) indicates that the full scale computation should not take placeany value greater than 0 represents the interval of full scale metric computation.
  • write_interval_volumes: Writes out the output volume at each iteration. It helps to present the registration process as a short movie a value of 0 (the default) indicates that this option should not take placeany value greater than 0 represents the interval between the iterations which outputs are written to the disk.
  • collapse_output_transforms: Collapse output transforms. Specifically, enabling this option combines all adjacent transforms where possible. All adjacent linear transforms are written to disk in the form of an itk affine transform (called xxxGenericAffine.mat). Similarly, all adjacent displacement field transforms are combined when written to disk (e.g. xxxWarp.nii.gz and xxxInverseWarp.nii.gz (if available)). Also, an output composite transform including the collapsed transforms is written to the disk (called outputCollapsed(Inverse)Composite).
  • initialize_transforms_per_stage: Initialize linear transforms from the previous stage. By enabling this option, the current linear stage transform is directly intialized from the previous stage's linear transform; this allows multiple linear stages to be run where each stage directly updates the estimated linear transform from the previous stage. (e.g. Translation -> Rigid -> Affine).
  • interpolation: Several interpolation options are available in ITK. These have all been made available. Currently the interpolator choice is only used to warp (and possibly inverse warp) the final output image(s).
  • restrict_deformation: This option allows the user to restrict the optimization of the displacement field, translation, rigid or affine transform on a per-component basis. For example, if one wants to limit the deformation or rotation of 3-D volume to the first two dimensions, this is possible by specifying a weight vector of '1x1x0' for a deformation field or '1x1x0x1x1x0' for a rigid transformation. Low-dimensional restriction only works if there are no preceding transformations.All stages up to and including the desired stage must have this option specified,even if they should not be restricted (in which case specify 1x1x1...).
  • initial_fixed_transform: Specify the initial fixed transform(s) which get immediately incorporated into the composite transform. The order of the transforms is stack-esque in that the last transform specified on the command line is the first to be applied. In addition to initialization with ITK transforms, the user can perform an initial translation alignment by specifying the fixed and moving images and selecting an initialization feature. These features include using the geometric center of the images (=0), the image intensities (=1), or the origin of the images (=2).
  • initial_moving_transform: Specify the initial moving transform(s) which get immediately incorporated into the composite transform. The order of the transforms is stack-esque in that the last transform specified on the command line is the first to be applied. In addition to initialization with ITK transforms, the user can perform an initial translation alignment by specifying the fixed and moving images and selecting an initialization feature. These features include using the geometric center of the images (=0), the image intensities (=1), or the origin of the images (=2).
  • winsorize_image_intensities: Winsorize data based on specified quantiles.
  • masks: Image masks to limit voxels considered by the metric. Two options are allowed for mask specification: 1) Either the user specifies a single mask to be used for all stages or 2) the user specifies a mask for each stage. With the latter one can select to which stages masks are applied by supplying valid file names. If the file does not exist, a mask will not be used for that stage. Note that we handle the fixed and moving masks separately to enforce this constraint.
  • minc: Use MINC file formats for transformations.
  • random_seed: Random seed.
  • verbose: Verbose output.
  • float_: Use 'float' instead of 'double' for computations.
  • runner: Command runner.
Returns:

NamedTuple of outputs (described in AntsRegistrationOutputs).
